    "updated_at": "2016-02-11T19:24:47Z",
    "body": "So this may be a really kludgy way to address the issue, but changing [line 37 of `atom/browser/api/frame_subscriber.cc`](https://github.com/atom/electron/blob/master/atom/browser/api/frame_subscriber.cc#L37) to check whether the frame subscriber's isolate is the current one seems to solve the issue for me:\n\n``` cpp\nvoid FrameSubscriber::OnFrameDelivered(\n    scoped_refptr<media::VideoFrame> frame, base::TimeTicks, bool result) {\n  if (!result || v8::Isolate::GetCurrent() != isolate_)\n    return;\n\n  v8::Locker locker(isolate_);\n  ...\n```\n\nIt also only hits that condition onceâ€”after returning early there, calls to `OnFrameDelivered()` stop. I also noticed that, when the crash is about to happen, the `EndFrameSubscription()` call is coming _in between_ associated calls to `FrameSubscriber::ShouldCaptureFrame()` and `FrameSubscriber::OnFrameDelivered()`. So it would seem that `EndFrameSubscription()` is effectively and safely stopping new uses of the frame subscriber, but any callbacks that have already been retrieved from the frame subscriber are still called.\n"
  },
